d the shame he felt using the foodbank having taken on a zero hours contract. Pregnant Jessica walked two miles to the foodbank because she couldn't afford public transport. This provocative book provides a much needed voice for foodbank users and volunteers in the UK, and a powerful insight into the realities of foodbank use from the inside.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aFood bankszGreat Britain. 0aPovertyzGreat Britain. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Agriculture & Food (see also POLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Agriculture & Food Policy).2bisacsh1 aMonroe, Jack, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBristol UP/Policy Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z9783111196435oZDB-23-BUPP0 cprintz978144732911440uhttps://doi.org/10.56687/9781447329121?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781447329121423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781447329121/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-BUPPb2016